{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_jemhadar_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383346162/1937121601/0948.xml":{"full_text":"Telephone\n2200\nIG OF PANAY\nJapanese Bluejacket Compan\nto Honor Dead at Scene\nof Tragedy\nREGRET AGAIN EMPHASIZED\nHull Declares Japanese Surface\nShips Machine-Gunned\nBombed Vessel\n(By the Associated Press)\nRear Admiral TWso Mi tsunami,\nchief of Japanese naval aerial opera\ntions, wa* relieved of hli poet Thurs\nday as a result of the bombing of the\nUnited States gunboat Panay.\nDomel (Japanese news agency)\nwhich carried the announcement of\nhis removal, declared the Japanese\ngovernment was acting swiftly to\ncarry out its pledge to America to\npunish officers responsible for the at\ntack.\nIt was explained that Mitsunami\nwas recalled because most bombard\nments in China had been carried out\nby naval planes.\nYoung Officer* Blamed\nForeign military and naval observ\ners In Shanghai said they believed\nthe Panay bombing and other attacks\nmay have been made by young officers\nwho had disregarded efforts of com'\nmanders to control their actions.\nA miniature fleet of American and\nBritish naval vessels bearing the three\ndead and most of the survivors of the\nPanay Incident was expected to reach\nShanghai some time Friday.\nIn Washington Secretary Hull an-,\nnounced official reports had con\nfirmed that Japanese surface vessels\nmachine-gunned the Panay after it\nhad been bombed from the air by\nJapanese naval fliers.\nHull gave no complete detaUsof the\nInformation received by the state\ndepartment concerning the machine\ngun attack.\nPlan Triunphal Entry\nJapanese forces, meanwhile, planned\nformal triumphal entry Into fallen\nNanking for Friday afternoon, while\nother Japanese columns continued\ntheir push Into the Interior.\nJapanese officials announced that\nthe American embassy building and\nother embassy and legation head\nquart\nera at Nanking were not damaged in\nthe siege of the city. All Americans\nand foreigners who remained there\nwere reported safe.\nArthur Menken, Paramount news\nreel cameraman who went through the\nsiege, wirelessed from the American\ngunboat Oahu that' \"Nanking is a\nshambles.\"\nChinese said their troops had re\nformed in an attempt to halt three\nJapanese columns along routes Japa\nnese were expected to take in their\ndrive on Hankow, one of the in\nterior cities where Chinese govern\nment ministries were established.\nIn Tokyo, the Japanese navy min\nistry announced that a company of\nbluejackets would be detailed to honor\nthe victims of the Panay bombing at\nthe spot on the Yangtze river where\nthey were killed.\nUnprecedented Gesture\nThe formal naval salute will be an\nunprecedented gesture which authori\nties said was the highest possible vol\nuntary tribute of one nation to an\nother.\nAuthoritative sources said the\nplanned salute was not connected\nwith the American protest against\nthe attack.\nThe admiralty Issued a statement\nreiterating Japanese regret over the\nIncident, adding that the navy \"has\ndecided to detail a company of blue\njackets to the spot to honor the\ndead.\"\nIt was announced also that sailors\nof the Japanese third fleet were col\nlecting 5,000 yen ($1,450) to be con\ntributed to the United States navy.\nForeign Minister Kokl Hlrote told\nthe cabinet council that the foreign\nministry was trying to devise a \"sat\nisfactory settlement\" of the Panay\nIncident.\nHirota explained to the cabinet\ncouncil that his department had \"ex\npressed a deep feeling of regret\" for\nthe Japanese attack on the United\nStates Yangtze river gunboat and\nthree Standard Oil vessels.\n'Show Understanding'\n\"Both the United States and Brit\nain apparently are showing more signs\nof understanding of the unhappy in\ncident than previously.\" Hirota said.\n'Likewise, public opinion of the te\nspective countries seems more fa\nvorable toward Japan.\"\nA qualified government official sol\nemnly declared that Japan would\nmeet the demands presented In the\nUnited States protest but said Em\nperor Hlrohito had not entered the\nnegotiations.\n(President Rosevelt's memorandum\nto Secretary Hull the day after the\nattack asked him to tell the Japanese\nambassador to Washington that the\npresident was \"deeply shocked\" and\n\"that be suggests that the emperor\nbe so advised.\")\n\"Hie negotiations at present are\nentirely between the governments,\"\nthe high official said. \"Therefore his\nmajesty la not a part of the picture.\nThe American note will reoelve a\nreply within a few days.\n\"Japan's answer will meet the de\nmands. It (the American protest)\nwas very firm but government offi\ncials unanimously considered It en\ntirely correct and proper.\"\ns\\^\nV'\nFRESH GLUES IN\nCORCORAN DEATH\nGun Used in Slaying Labor\nLeader Nov. 17 May Have\nBeen Sent From Spain\nMinneapolis, Dec. 18.\u2014\u2014Police\nInvestigation of the month-old slay\ning of Patrick J. Corcoran, labor lead\ner, spurted Thursday as authorities\nworked on clues they Indicated may\nbe of major importance in clearing\nup the mystery.\nTo the fact that balls tics experts be\nlieve the death bullet was fired from\na Spanish gun. Investigators have\nadded the report that a former Min\nneapolis resident, now fighting with\nthe Loyalist forces in Spain, sent a\ngun here from that country. They\nrefused to divulge the man's name.\nThey stated, however, the man Is\nwanted here on a charge of abandon'\nlng his family to join the Spanish\narmy.\nCorcoran, a leader in American Fed\neratlon of Labor circles here, was shot\nthe night of Nov. 17.\nThe slaying, precipitated a whole\nsale Investigation of labor organiza\ntion conditions in Minneapolis.\nMayville to Hear of\nRevised River Plan\nMayville, N. D., Dec. 16\u2014(#)\u2014Re\nvised projects and decreased cost pro\nposals in the plan for stream flow\nregulation and sewage disposal for\nthe Goose river basin will be pre\nsented to citizens of Mayville and\nHillsboro here Monday night, noyd\nJennings and Oscar Becker of the\nstate planning board will explain the\nplan at the meeting called by B. E.\nCondit of the Mayville Civic and\nCommerce association.\nDr. Yeager, whose work in plant\nbreeding here has made him famous,\nwill be with the experiment station\nat Michigan state, working with vege-\nHe also will teach part time.\nDr. Yeager resigned from NDAC in\nOctober, effective Jan. 1 stating at\nthe time: \"To anyone familiar with\nthe situation at the A. C., my reasons\nshould be obvious.\"\nHis statement was Interpreted to\nrefer to the state board ol administra\ntion's dtoml\u2014I of seven staff col\nleagues. and to aaw policies at the in-\nPresident Speaks to Japan's Emperor\nof gtbta\ntatll.t&e Japanese Aabftisador *ften\n6'cloekt\ntnt Is deepiy smutted\nsejrnett toy new* of India\n\u00bbte toa\u00abfeLrneh*\net\nJkaericaa and other\nvessels oo the'fangtse*\nkfc be wmgearte that the Sapnot\n\u00abo wMMd. V\nt\u00bb 'are being \u00bb*seM\u00bbX\u00abd\npresent** to -the\n*n ts hopedMthe^\n,.fx#re\u00bb$lan\u00bb of r*\u00bb\ntret proffer of mi\nffQU^paaa'tlon:\nJNfthal* \u00abtMuraateein| u|\u00bblo\u00abe\ny v\nI v Jv Trrf I*iM lif'\"'IWI^''\u2022-tVi'-ITr'S\nLaud Personnel\nChanges at AC\nPOLICE WORK ON\nShifts That Drew Strong Criti\ncism Called 'Step Forward'\nin College Audit\nPersonnel changes at the state ag\nricultural college which brought strong\ncriticism were described Thursday as\n\"a step forward\" in the audit report\nof the state board of administration\nwhich also charged political activity\nby some faculty members.\n\"The shattered morale caused by\nthe dictatorial manner of some\ndeans and assistant deans was very\npronounced,\" the report said. \"Your\nexaminer found removal of some of\nthe more pronounced offenders, and\ncurbing of authority of others, has\nhad a wholesale effect In rebuilding\nmorale and a noticeable improvement\nhas taken place.\"\nThe report was signed by M. T.\nChemick, Bismarck, as special exam\niner and F. F. Bur chard. Grand Porks,\nas collaborator.\nCorrespondence from files of various\nfaculty members was reproduced in\nthe report which concluded that a\ncentralized system of accounting for\nall funds should be Inaugurated.\nLetter Reveals Interest\nThe report accused Dean R. M.\nDolve of the engineering department\nof advocating closing the Mayville,.El\nlendale and Bottineau schools. The\nexaminers said a letter from the dean's\nnephew, Samuel Dolve, written from\nBismarck during the 1935 legislative\nsession, showed the dean was inter'\nested and mentioned an anticipated\n'scrap\" the proposal would develop\nin the legislative assembly.\nThe report said Dean H. L. Walster,\ndirector of the extension division, waa\nengaged in some 27 governmental ac\ntivities and \"no one man should be\nexpected to do well all the things.\"\nMany cases of relatives getting Jobs\nthrough professors and administrative\nheads were revealed by he audit, the\nreport said.\nFundamental Honesty Unquestioned\n\"The lax manner in which finances\nol institutions were handled by many\ndepartment heads and employes\" was\n(Continued on Page Two)\nPlant Wizard at NDAC\nAccepts Michigan Post\nFargo, h. D., Dec. 16.\u2014(JP\u2014Dr. A. P.\nYeager, North Dakota Agricultural\ncollege horticulturist, will leave short\nly after Christmas to join the staff\nof Michigan State college at Eaat Lan\nsing.\nV A\nTHE BISMARCK TRIBUNE\nHow the President sharpened the\ntone of his note to Secretary Hull,\n\"requesting\" rather than \"suggesting'\nthat the killing of Americans in China\nbe called specifically to the attention\nof the Japanese emperor by his am\nbassador, Is shown in the facsimile of\nthe White House note at left, with the\nword \"suggests\" crossed out and\namended in the presidential hand\nJapanese Ambassador Hirosi Sal\nto\npulled deeply on a cigaret, above, as\nhe waited at the State Department to\nsee Secretary Hull and express \"deep\nregret\" over the sinking of the gun'\nboat Panay.\nMAY CONSTRUCT 7\nIRRIGATION DAMS\nON CEDAR RIVER\nWould Impound Runoff Waters\nBetween Sioux, Grant Coun\nties WPA Help Sought\nAgreement to sponsor construction\nof seven dams In the Cedar river\nthe Sioux-Grant county border was\nreached by the North Dakota Water\nConservation commission at its meet\ning ending here Thursday.\nThe dams, each about three feet\nhigh, will Impound run-off water and\nmake it available for Irrigating small\ntracts along the banks.\nThe North Dakota Rural Rehablll'\ntatlon corporation also approved the\nproposal and will furnish the money.\nApplication for WPA help In con\nstruction of the dams will be made\nat once.\nCAunty commissioners of Sioux\ncounty agreed to designate the county\nas a water conservation district and\nto levy a tax of one-half mill to sup\nport the project. The area to be bene'\nflted also will be orgalnsed into a dis\ntrict and special assessments will be\nlevied on the land benefited to make\nup the balance.\n\"The commission has wanted to take\nat least one stream and give It com'\nplete development for experimental\npurposes and to test out the value of\nagriculture of such a program,\" Vice\nChairman Henry Holt explained.\n\"This application from Sioux county\npermits us to do so In an area where\nthe need for Improvement is manifest\nand where the proposal has the whole\nhearted support of the people In the\ndistrict.\"\nReports on the Lewis and Clark irri\ngation project disclosed that WPA\nworkers are expected to go on the\nproject on Dec. 31 and that other\nphases of the work are being pushed\nas fast as possible.\nIt also was disclosed that prepara\ntlons to begin work In the Painted\nWoods Irrigation district, In southern\nMcLean and northern Burleigh coun\nties will be pOshed as rapidly as pos\nsible.\nDewey Johnson Hurt\nAs Car Skids, Upsets\nInjured when the car in which he\nand several other persons were re\nturning from a dance early Thursday\nmorning skidded on the icy road and\nrolled over, Dewey Johnson, New\nSalem, was in a hospital here Thurs\nday recovering from severe bruises\nabout the chest, shoulders and head.\nJohnson said he was driving when\nthe accident occurred near Sweet\nbriar. The car was badly damaged,\nhe said. Johnson waa brought to the\nhospital at about 4 a. m. Thursday\nwith two others who were treated for\nminor injuries and returned to their\nhomes.\nRay Winters, Shields,\nDies in Local Hospital\nRay Winters, 30, Shields, N. D- died\nin a hospital here at 5:13 a. m. Thurs\nday. He had been in the hospital since\nSunday. Winters leaves, In addition to\nhis widow, his mother and two step\nchildren.\nFuneral services were tentatively\nfor 10 a. m. Saturday In the\nShields Catholic church, with Father\nPtands officiating. Neighbors will be\npallbearers.\nThe body will remain in the Oalnan\nfuneral home here until it\nIs\nto Shields PWday.\nNorth Dakota's Oldest Newspaper\nESTABLISHED 1873 BISMARCK, N. D\u201e THURSDAY, DECEMBER 16, 1937 PRICE FIVE CENTS\nSentiment to Renew Spending Grows\nHigh Japanese Naval Official Relieved of Post\nREMOVAL OP TEIZO\nMITSUNAMI FOLLOWS\nFEDERAL FUNDS TO\nAID WESTERN N. D.\nREQUESTED BY CRAY\nState Treasurer Tells Mclntyre\n$1,500,000 Is Needed to\nAlleviate Suffering\nWOULD ASSIST 250,000\nExecutive Order, Congressional\nAppropriation Are Possi\nble Channels\nWashington, Dec. 16.\u2014(JP)\u2014The\nplight of thousands of North Dako\nta ns, described by John Gray, atate\ntreasurer, as facing starvation and\nfreezing, was brought to the attention\nThursday of Marvin Mclntyre, secre\ntary to President Roosevelt.\nGray asked for at least $1,500,000 in\nfederal relief funds for 300,000 to 250,\n000 persons In the western North Da\nkota counties.\nThe state, Gray told Mclntyre, was\nfinancially unable to do anything,\nstate and county treasuries in the af\nfected area were in the red, cold\nweather prevented instituting work\nprojects, and delinquent taxes were\nuncollectible.\nGray was advised North Dakota\nahould show good faith by utilizing all\nIts resources to help In the crisis. In\nthis connection, it was pointed out that\nwhile the state and counties had virt\nually reached their bonding limits, the\nstate still had about $600,000 to go\nbefore reaching the limit on general\nobligation bonds.\nGray was unable to say what Gov.\nLanger's attitude would be in this\nrespect. North Dakota congressmen\npointed out it would require a special\nsession to authorise such bonds.\nOray was told funds he asked were\nnot available but could be approprlat\ned by ooQDWtf.'\nRep. William Lemke (Rep.-N. D.)\nsaid later dust bowl congressmen\nprobably would Introduce a bill call\ning for a 115,000,000 appropriation for\nrelief In the dust bowl area.\nLemke said the prairie states group\nin the-house would meet Saturday to\nconsider the situation and while hop\ning to get some relief by executive\norder would seek congressional action\nif they failed.\nGOVERNOR NOT\nAVAILABLE FOR COMMENT\nGov. William Langer could net be\nreached Immediately for comment on\nwhether a special session of the leg\nislature would be needed to meet the\nproblems outlined at Washington by\nState Treasurer John Gray.\nMfllTiiiiS\nPUUMP\nHomer Petit Succeeds A. D.\nScott, Other Officers Named\nat State Meeting\nValley City, N. D., Dec. 15\u2014m\u2014\nHomer O. Petit, Fargo, was elected\npresident of the North Dakota State\nPoultry association at the 44th annual\nexhibit here Wednesday. He suooeeds\nA. D, Scott of Fargo.\nS. L. Huey, Devils Lake Mrs. James\nThoreson, Flngal and O. B. Skonnard.\nValley City, were named first, second\nand third vice presidents, respectively\nO. A. Barton, Fargo, secretary, and\nLeander Bratland, Lisbon, superin\ntendent.\nThe association voted to adopt the\nsuggestion of Frank E. Moore, NDAC\nextension poultry man, that North Da\nkota be organized to have a part in\nthe world congress at Cleveland, Ohio,\nin 1S39.\nJohn van Leeuwen, Oriska, exhibited\nthe championship turkey.\nMrs. E. G. Patterson's\nFather Dies in Pueblo\nMrs. E. G. Patterson, 433 Main ave\nnue, left Wednesday evening for\nPueblo, Colo., where ahe was called\nby the death of her father, Edward\nJudge. Accompanying Mrs. Patter\nson was her mother, Mrs. Judge, who\nhas been here visiting.\nMr.'Judge's death occurred unex\npectedly Wednesday at 1:30 a. m.\nafter a brief Illness. Funeral services\nwill be held Friday at 9 a. m. in Pueblo.\nIn addition to his wife and Mrs.\nPatterson, he is survived by two other\ndaughters, Mrs. McLaughlin, San\nFrancisco, Calif., and Mrs. Ranger,\nPueblo.\nMr. Judge, who was 87 years old,\nwas visiting his daughter, Mrs. Ran\nger, at the time of his death. His\nhome waa in San Francisco.\nJury Finally.Frees\nWoman From Chair\nEdenburg, Pa., Dec. 18.\u2014(JP)\u2014Wan\nMrs. Margaret Karmendl. twloe sen\ntenced to die in the electric chair, es\ncaped that fate Thursday as the third\njury to try her for the railroad spike\nslaying of a son returned a verdict of\nsecond degree murder, ttm verdict\ncarries a penalty of 1 to 9ft years in\nthe penitentiary.\nLanger, Olson Aid\nOpen Heart Drive\nGovernor and Mayor Appeal to\nCitizens to Aid Campaign,\nAttend Ball\nTaking cognizance of misforune and\ndistress in North Dakota, particularly\namong children, Gov. William Langer\nThursday urged citizens to give aid\nand support to Bismarck's Open Your\nHeart campaign and recommended\nthe Charity Ball next Wednesday\nevening in the World War Memorial\nbuilding as a worthwhile undertaking\non behalf of the poor children of the\ncity.\nMayor Obert A. Olson of Bismarck\njoined with the governor in pro\nclaiming the worthiness of the objeo\ntlves of the campaign and likewise\nendorsed the charity ball as an ave\nnue by which the citizens can help\ntheir unforunate fellows.\n$58.50 Added to\nChristmas 'Kitty'\nCash contributions to the Open\nYour Heart campaign increased\nduring the past 34 hours as head\nquarters reported receipt of 17 dif\nferent gifts of money.\nThe tabulation Thursday morn\ning was:\nPreviously reported (375.00\nUCT Auxiliary 6.00\nDr. K. W. Morris 5.00\nMr. and Mrs. Walter Vater.. 5.00\nA friend 5.00\nSunshine club 3.50\nLewis and Clark Study club 3.00\nMrs. Wesley Baker 3.00\nMrs. J. C. Hanson 1.00,\nJ. R. Brecden family 1.00\nJ. P. French 5.00\nProgressive Mothers club... 5.00\nA friend 6.00\nMinneshoshe Chapter DAR 5.00\nUnion Ladies' Aid (Gorham,\nN. D.) 3.00\nH. E. Hanson 3.00\nO. A. JOnas 1.00\nTrinity Lutheran Sewing\nclub 3^)0\nTotal to date *333.50\nMake checks payable to Open\nYour Heart campaign and mail to\nOpen Your Heart headquarters,\n330 Main avenue, Bismarck.\nAll proceeds of the ball, under the\nchairmanship of Milton Rue, will be\ndevoted to relieving distress and\nmaking Christmas a happier day for\nhundreds of kiddles In the Capital\nCity.\nCash contributions showed a slight\nincrease in both number and sise dur\ning the last 34 hours and Campaign\nChairman G. A. Dahlen said that\n(Continued on Page Two)\nHanford Speeding: Up\nSchedule to Denver\nFastest service ever offered between\nBismarck and Denver and San Fran\ncisco was annoflnced Thursday by\nMalcolm L. Boss, general traffic man\nager of Hanford arillnes, following a\nchange in schedules calling for a de\nparture from Bismarck at 12:50 p. m.\nand arrival in Denver at 9:55 p. m.\nThe new schedule becomes effective\nsimulanteously with a substantial re\nduction in fares, and the entire flight\nis made In twin-engined transports,\nHanford being used to Omaha where\nconnections are made with United\nAir Lines' evening plane for Denver\nand Pacific Coast points.\nThere is similar speedy service from\nColorado's capital, as passengers, mail\nand express leaving there at midnight\n(1:18 a. m.) arrive In Bismarck at\n11:43 a. m.\nHOOVER TO TALK\nChcago, Dec. 16. Former\nPresident Herbert Hoover came to\nChicago Thursday to give what his\nspokesman said would be a non\npolitical address on economics. He\nwill speak tonight before the Economic\nclub of Chicago.\nLewis Girdler\nhis dream of seeing the nation's mill\nin unionism.\nbanded toghel\nhas come true.'*\nlite founder of\namid a wild dei\nof the first\nSWOC,\nCIO, welcomed\ntion to the floor\ncongress of\nGirdler, presi\u00ad\ndent of the Republic Steel corpora\ntion.\n'X' Marks Spot\nNo mistletoe for ultra-modern\nstudents of the University of\nOmaha, Neb. Co-eds are \"put on\nthe spot\"\u2014a huge red circle and\ncross painted on a campus side\nwalk\u2014and each girl who finds\nherself caught in the circle with a\nyoung man must pay with aAkiss\n\u2014as did AUce Jane Vickery\n\"caught\" with David Hill, above.\nSLAYER OF FORMER\nN. D. COUPLE WILL\nHANG JANUARY 15\nFrank Robideau, Escaped N. Y.\nConvict, Pleads Guilty to\nFirst Degree Murder\nColumbus, Mont., Dec. 16.\u2014(AO\nDistrict Judge Ben Harwood Wednes\nday sentenced Frank Robideau, also\nknown as Joseph Liberty, to hang Jan.\n15 for the slaying of Mike Kuntz,\nWheat Basin, Mont., elevator oper\nator.\nHie 47-year-old farmer, who con\nfessed he was an escaped New York\nconvict, pleaded guilty to a first de\ngree murder charge last Saturday.\nHe has pleaded innocent to a sim\nilar Indictment resulting from the\ndeath of Mrs. Kuntz.\nMr. and Mrs. Kuntz, neighbors of\nRobideau and former North Dakotans,\nwere shot to death along a highway\nNov. 36. Robideau, in a signed con\nfession announced by County Attorney\nP. R. Heily, said the two men had\nagreed to \"shoot out\" an argument\nover ownership of some wheat.\nLarry Kuntz, 5-year-old son of the\nslain couple, was severely beaten\nabout the head but survived and\nidentified Robideau as the killer of\nboth his parents.\nANETA WOMAN DIES\nAneta, N. D., Dec. 16.\u2014(/Pi\u2014Funeral\nrites for Mrs. Christine Stegen, 72,\nwho died at her home near here Tues\nday night, will be Sunday in the Sogn\nLutheran church.\nTom Girdler Branded\n'Murderer' by Lewis\nPittsburgh, Dec. 16.\u2014(/P)\u2014John L.\nLewis denounced operators of \"Little\nSteel\" Thursday and told an uproar\nious convention of steel workers that\nThe shaggy-haired labor leader took\nthe platform only after a delay of 20\nminutes by the ovation, and then de\nclared:\n\"You have found out for the first\ntime In your respective lives that you\ncould organize if you wanted to or\nganize.\"\nTurning suddenly to speak of the\nsteel operators, and the strike In \"Lit\ntle Steel\" companies last year, he went\non:\n\"The name of Girdler should be\nsynonomous with that terrible word,\n'murder,' because Girdler murdered\nour members.\n\"Ihis union, like the Christisn\nchurch, Is founded upon the blood of\nman.\n\"No one need have any fear that a\nWeir or a Grace is going to desroy\nthis union in the future.\n\"No one need have any fear that a\nmurderer like Girdler can destroy this\nunion because it cannot be destroyed\nby murdering its members.\n\"Labor in America can do what it\nwants to do. The public is being told\nwhat you are thinking about and your\nvoice is heard for the first time.\"\nThe Weather\nPartly cloudy tonight,\nFriday little change\nin temperature.\nSOLONS LOOK WITH\nFAVOR ONAHEMPT\nII\nWage-Hour, Farm Bills Won't\nReach FR Before Session\nEnds, Says Bankhead\nHOUSING BILL APPROVED\nSponsors Will Seek Action\n'Stop-Recession' Program\nStatement Circulated\nWashington, Dec. 16.\u2014(JP)\u2014Strom\nsupport has developed in congress,\na survey showed Thursday, for re\nsumption of government spending on\na modified scale in an attempt to\nspur business activity.\nSome anti-administration senators\nas well as some Roosevelt supporters\nsaid they believed new spending must\nstart in January or February.\nWhile these comments were being\nmade, several senators disclosed they\nhad been urged to sign a public state\nment advocating a 10-point program\nto stop the business recession.\nThe steps suggested were revision\nof business taxes, approach toward a\nbalanced budget, \"just relations be\ntween capital and labor,\" reliance or\nprofitable investment of private sav\nings, recognition of the profit motive\nand superiority of the competitive\nsystem, assuranoe of the safety of\ncollateral, reduction In the general\ntax burden, maintenance of states'\nrights, economical and non-political\ndistribution of relief, and preserva\ntion of the American system of pri\nvate enterprise.\nSenator Bailey Dem., N. C.) said\nhe was one of the authors and the\nfinal editor of the statement.\n'There was a general feeling in\nthe senate,\" Bailey stated, \"that there\nought to be an understanding between\neach other on what should be done\nabout the business recession.\"\nAmong those advocating greater\nspending was Senator I* Folletta\n(Prog.-Wis.), who said an Increase in\nworks progress expenditures would be\nlikely to provide business with a tem\nporary impetus.\nAdministration leaders tried bard Id\ncomplete the writing\noi\nfarm and\nwages and hours hills, but Speaks'\nBankhead said there was little chance\neither would, reach the White Housa\nbefore the special session ends next\nweek.\nConferences Must Follow\nThe speaker said he was informed\nthe senate hoped to pass its crop con\ntrol bill within a few days. The housa\nis struggling over a wages and hours\nmeasure.\nPassage of the farm bill by the sen\nate and of the labor bill by the house,\nhowever, must be followed by confer\nences between committees of the two\nhouses to compose differences in theis\nbills.\nWilliam Green, adding to the sen\u00bb\neral congressional confusion, asked th\u00bb\nhouse to send its wages and hours bill\nback to the committee. The president\nof the American Federation of Labor\nsent telegrams to all representatives\nas debate was at its height.\nThe senate refused Thursday to\nsubstitute a domestic allotment cot\nton program for the compulsory cotton\nsection of the ever-normal granary\nbill.\nThe senate struck from its farm\nbill a provision which would have pro\nhibited benefit payments to farmers\nwho failed to produce \"food and feed\ncrops sufficient to meet home con\nsumption.\"\nApprove House Bill\nThe house banking committee ap\nproved the administration's bill de\nsigned to encourage construction ol\nup to $16,000,000,000 of privately fi\nnanced new homes.\nCommittee members said they would\nattempt to obtain consideration of the\nmeasure after the house disposes of\nIts current business-wage-hour legis\nlation.\nMembers of the house committee\nsaid that in the bill they approved\nno change was made in a provision for\nreducing from 5'4 to 5 per cent the\ninterest and service charge allowed to\ninstitutions making loans insured b$\nthe federal housing administration.\nThe committee, they said, stood by a\nprevious decision to permit ten pet\ncent down payments and 90 per cent\n(Continued on Page Two)\nCHRISTMAS\nSUPERSTITIONS\nNothing'sown on Christmas Eve\nwill perish even though the seed\nis planted in the snow, accord\ning to an ancient Netherlands\nsuperstition.\n7\nSk9ppi*f\n*tUl GklUtM*","height":"27060","width":"20584"}}
